SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 4749
A bill to amend 1961 PA 236, entitled
"Revised judicature act of 1961,"
by amending sections 810a, 8151, and 8176 (MCL 600.810a, 600.8151,
and 600.8176), section 810a as amended by 2011 PA 300, section 8151
as amended by 2012 PA 33, and section 8176 as amended by 2022 PA 7.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF MICHIGAN ENACT:
1 Sec. 810a. (1) The probate judges in the counties of Arenac,
2 Crawford, Iron, Kalkaska, Crawford, Lake, Iron, and Ontonagon have
3 the jurisdiction, powers, duties, and title of a district judge
4 within their respective counties, in addition to the jurisdiction,
5 powers, duties, and title of a probate judge.
6 (2) Beginning January 2, 2007, in addition to the probate
7 judges described in subsection (1), the probate judges in the
SCS H03845'25 (H-1) c2vwak

2
1 counties of Alcona, Baraga, Benzie, Missaukee, Montmorency, Oscoda,
2 and Presque Isle have the jurisdiction, powers, duties, and title
3 of a district judge within their respective counties, in addition
4 to the jurisdiction, powers, duties, and title of a probate judge.
5 (3) In counties where the only district judgeship is being
6 eliminated and the section in chapter 81 that governs that district
7 court district provides that this section applies, the probate
8 judge in that county shall have the jurisdiction, powers, duties,
9 and title of a district judge within that county, in addition to
10 the jurisdiction, powers, duties, and title of a probate judge.
11 (4) In addition to the probate judges described in subsections
12 (1) and (2), the probate judge in the county of Antrim has the
13 jurisdiction, powers, duties, and title of a district judge within
14 the county of Antrim, in addition to the jurisdiction, powers,
15 duties, and title of a probate judge.
16 Sec. 8151. (1) Except as provided in subsection (2), the
17 eighty-sixth The eighty-sixth-A district consists of the county of
18 Antrim and is a district of the first class. Under section 810a,
19 the Antrim County probate judge shall serve as judge of the eighty-
20 sixth-A district.
21 (2) The eighty-sixth-B district consists of the counties of
22 Grand Traverse , Antrim, and Leelanau, is a district of the first
23 class, and has 3 2 judges. The district judges of the eighty-sixth
24 district court who are serving as of the effective date of this
25 amendatory act shall continue to serve as the incumbent judges of
26 the eighty-sixth-B district court.
27 (2) Beginning on the earlier of the following dates, the
28 eighty-sixth district has 2 judges:
29 (a) The date on which a vacancy occurs in the office of
SCS H03845'25 (H-1) c2vwak

3
1 district judge in the eighty-sixth district.
2 (b) The beginning date of the term for which an incumbent
3 district judge in the eighty-sixth district no longer seeks
4 election or reelection to that office.
5 Sec. 8176. (1) Except as otherwise provided in this section,
6 if a new district is proposed by law, that new district is not
7 created and any district judgeship proposed for the district is not
8 authorized or filled by election unless each district control unit
9 in the proposed district, by resolution adopted by the governing
10 body of the district control unit, approves the creation of the new
11 district and each judgeship proposed for the district and unless
12 the clerk of each district control unit adopting that resolution
13 files a copy of the resolution with the state court administrator
14 not later than 4 p.m. of the sixteenth Tuesday preceding the August
15 primary for the election immediately preceding the effective date
16 of the new district. The state court administrator shall
17 immediately notify the elections division of the department of
18 state with respect to each new judicial district and district
19 judgeship authorized under this subsection.
20 (2) A resolution required under subsection (1) that is filed
21 before the effective date of the amendatory act that authorized
22 that new district is a valid approval for purposes of this section
23 only if the filing occurs within the 2-year state legislative
24 session during which the amendatory act was enacted. A resolution
25 required under subsection (1) that is filed after the effective
26 date of the amendatory act that authorized that new district is a
27 valid approval for purposes of this section only if the filing
28 occurs not later than 4 p.m. of the sixteenth Tuesday preceding the
29 August primary for the election immediately preceding the effective
SCS H03845'25 (H-1) c2vwak

4
1 date of the new district.
2 (3) By proposing a new district and 1 or more district
3 judgeships for the district, the legislature is not creating that
4 district or any judgeship in the district. If a district control
5 unit, acting through its governing body, approves the creation of a
6 new district and 1 or more district judgeships proposed by law for
7 that district, that approval constitutes an exercise of the
8 district control unit's option to provide a new activity or service
9 or to increase the level of activity or service offered in the
10 district control unit beyond that required by existing law, as the
11 elements of that option are defined by 1979 PA 101, MCL 21.231 to
12 21.244, and a voluntary acceptance by the district control unit of
13 all expenses and capital improvements which may result from the
14 creation of the new district and each judgeship. However, the
15 exercise of the option does not affect the state's obligation to
16 pay the same portion of each judge's salary which is paid by the
17 state to other district judges as provided by law, or to
18 appropriate and disburse funds to the district control unit for the
19 necessary costs of state requirements established by a state law
20 that becomes effective on or after December 23, 1978.
21 (4) Each district judgeship created under subsection (1) must
22 be filled by election under the Michigan election law, 1954 PA 116,
23 MCL 168.1 to 168.992. The first term of each district judgeship
24 shall be 6 years, unless the law permitting the creation of the new
25 district and 1 or more judgeships provides for a term of a
26 different length.
27 (5) The reformation of the seventy-eighth, seventy-ninth,
28 eighty-first, eighty-second, eighty-third, and eighty-seventh
29 judicial districts under 2002 PA 92 does not require the approval
SCS H03845'25 (H-1) c2vwak

5
1 of the district control unit under this section or section 8175.
2 (6) The reformation of the seventy-eighth and seventy-ninth
3 judicial districts under the amendatory act that added this
4 subsection 2022 PA 7 does not require the approval of the district
5 control unit under this section or section 8175.
6 (7) The reformation of the eighty-sixth-A and eighty-sixth-B
7 judicial districts under the amendatory act that added this
8 subsection does not require the approval of the district control
9 unit under this section.
10 Enacting section 1. This amendatory act takes effect 12 months
11 after the date it is enacted into law.
